comments: I've never enjoyed online therapy apps or self help apps, but so far I've rally enjoyed this one. learn_new_flourish: I've learned that taking a moment to reflect on my day usually helps to make me feel more accomplished with what I've done that day. yeah, I learned a bit about my behaviors and activities I can do to support myself. One thing I wish I knew was where to find all of those specific insights Sunnie gave. I can remember the definitions or the descriptions but not the names.
experience_flourish: It was really fun. At first I felt like I had to force myself to remember to open the app, but after a couple times, I found myself opening the app to talk to Sunnie rather than scroll on Instagram just for fun. I've actually really come to enjoy sharing with Sunnie about my day, about the good and bad things that happen and asking for help and advice from her. I've really enjoyed using the app.
takeaways_flourish: Talking with Sunnie was a bit like journaling in the sense that I got to slow down for a moment and really think about my day. It differed from journaling though because Sunnie would remind me of goals I set and would bring up previous conversations we had which made me begin to see certain patterns within myself. The majority of the last 6 weeks were difficult for me emotionally and I was surprised by how supported the app made me feel, specifically my conversations with Sunnie and the small activities she suggested. Even when I didn't feel very up to doing the activities, for example, listing 3 things I was grateful for, I found that once the task was completed, I felt a sense of accomplishment. I almost always ask for the science behind the activities/suggestions (I love this feature) so I know a lot of the activities are prompted specifically to help with my mood, but I think a happy side effect is the mood boost from taking on a task and being able to complete it.
feedback_flourish: I would compile a list of all of the science based facts that Sunnie gives so that I can revisit them. The names Sunnie gives are technical or a name of a study, so they're not always intuitive and easy to remember. I'd love to have a list of all of the science Sunnie has explained to me so I can learn more about it on my own time.
recommend_flourish: YES! I think anyone who uses this app can find something about it they enjoy. I think the conversations with Sunnie especially is what drew me in and I think it will for others as well. Even though it's AI, I really feel heard and understood with Sunnie. I feel supported when I speak to her about stressful events in my life and I feel like I can trust her to ask for advice without any judgment. For young adults especially I think a tool like this can be useful since this is a time in our lives where a lot of change is occurring, like transferring to new institutions, transitioning into being an adult, attempting to narrow down a choice for study, and try to do their best at balancing work, school, social life, etc... I know how helpful Sunnie has been for me so I can imagine it being helpful for others like me.

experience_flourish:
I thought the Flourish app was pleasing to look at and intuitive to use. I liked the small variances in visuals as it made the app not too boring to experience. I also liked the thought of Sunny being the sun and you are the plant that's growing, I thought that was a nice touch.

I did not talk to Sunny often but when I did I was glad there was a history of recaps. I have not tried to go back to continue a conversation to see whether Sunny is capable of "remembering" the previous conversation in a separate instance.

In terms of functional use, I mostly utilized the Pomodoro timer, mindful breathing, and three things I'm grateful for. I didn't look at the community aspect that much, but thought it was a nice option to have. I think the message and goal of the app comes across well. It's made with lots of love, and I can tell from the developers.
takeaways_flourish: Sunny will be there for me if I want to talk!
feedback_flourish:
I'd change the automatic "how are you feeling" scale that shows up upon opening the app. I just feel like it doesn't do much for me, personally. Or, I would put it on the home screen for the user to optionally tap rather than be obliged to tap.

I also would incorporate optional sound cues in the breathing app to change inhale, exhale, and hold. I like the vibration effect, but often it's not strong enough for me to be able to tell. For example, if I want to do mindful breathing while doing another activity, but doing the box breathing method, I find that I have to look at the app for visual cues of when to change my state, since the vibrations do not carry well and I don't think it would be good to make them stronger.
recommend_flourish: I think so, it's been a small tool I've been trying to remember to incorporate into my life and it hasn't brought any negatives to my life. I like that it has all sorts of features in one place and it would be helpful for students to practice emotional awareness and mindfulness.

learn_new_flourish: Yes, I learned how small habits like gratitude journaling or quick mindfulness exercises can boost my mood and focus. It showed me how impactful little moments of self-reflection can be.
experience_flourish: Using the Flourish app was a calming and positive experience. It felt like a simple way to stay mindful and check in with myself daily. The reminders were helpful without feeling overwhelming, and it became a nice part of my routine.
takeaways_flourish: Over the past six weeks, my biggest takeaway has been how powerful consistent small habits can be for overall well-being. The app helped me focus on mindfulness and gratitude, which I often overlook in my busy schedule. I also appreciated how it prompted me to set realistic goals and track my progress in a way that felt encouraging rather than overwhelming. It made me realize the importance of prioritizing mental health alongside academics and social commitments.
feedback_flourish: One thing I would change is the customization options. While the app is great, I sometimes felt that the daily prompts and reminders were too general and not tailored enough to my specific needs or goals. Adding more personalized features, like adapting content based on user preferences or feedback, would make it even more engaging and relevant. I’d also love to see a better integration of community support, maybe a feature for connecting with others who are working on similar goals.
recommend_flourish: Absolutely, I think it would be useful for universities to offer the Flourish app as a wellness tool. College life can be stressful, and having an accessible, user-friendly app focused on mindfulness, goal-setting, and emotional well-being could make a real difference for students. The app could be particularly helpful for students who might not feel comfortable seeking in-person counseling or who need a supplementary tool to manage stress. By offering it through the university, it could also signal a stronger commitment to supporting student wellness, which is so important in today’s fast-paced academic environment.
